<Link id="l00009" /><CodeLine lineNumber="9"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; This is the main file that defines all the data structure, signature,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00010" /><CodeLine lineNumber="10"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; constant literals that are shared across profiling runtime library,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00011" /><CodeLine lineNumber="11"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; compiler (instrumentation), and host tools (reader/writer). The entities</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00012" /><CodeLine lineNumber="12"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; defined in this file affect the profile runtime ABI, the raw profile format,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00013" /><CodeLine lineNumber="13"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; or both.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00014" /><CodeLine lineNumber="14"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00015" /><CodeLine lineNumber="15"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The file has two identical copies. The primary copy lives in LLVM and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00016" /><CodeLine lineNumber="16"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; the other one  sits in compiler-rt/lib/profile directory. To make changes</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00017" /><CodeLine lineNumber="17"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; in this file, first modify the primary copy and copy it over to compiler-rt.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00018" /><CodeLine lineNumber="18"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Testing of any change in this file can start only after the two copies are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00019" /><CodeLine lineNumber="19"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; synced up.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00020" /><CodeLine lineNumber="20"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00021" /><CodeLine lineNumber="21"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The first part of the file includes macros that defines types, names, and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00022" /><CodeLine lineNumber="22"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; initializers for the member fields of the core data structures. The field</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00023" /><CodeLine lineNumber="23"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; declarations for one structure is enabled by defining the field activation</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00024" /><CodeLine lineNumber="24"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; macro associated with that structure. Only one field activation record</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00025" /><CodeLine lineNumber="25"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; can be defined at one time and the rest definitions will be filtered out by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00026" /><CodeLine lineNumber="26"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; the preprocessor.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="27"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="28"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Examples of how the template is used to instantiate structure definition:</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00200" /><CodeLine lineNumber="200"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42; For indirect function call value profiling, the addresses of the target</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00201" /><CodeLine lineNumber="201"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; functions are profiled by the instrumented code. The target addresses are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00202" /><CodeLine lineNumber="202"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; written in the raw profile data and converted to target function name&#39;s MD5</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00203" /><CodeLine lineNumber="203"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; hash by the profile reader during deserialization.  Typically, this happens</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00204" /><CodeLine lineNumber="204"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; when the raw profile data is read during profile merging.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00205" /><CodeLine lineNumber="205"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00206" /><CodeLine lineNumber="206"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; For this remapping the ProfData is used.  ProfData contains both the function</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00207" /><CodeLine lineNumber="207"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; name hash and the function address.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00208" /><CodeLine lineNumber="208"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00385" /><CodeLine lineNumber="385"><Highlight kind="comment">   &#42; The first element of the array that stores the number of profiled</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00386" /><CodeLine lineNumber="386"><Highlight kind="comment">   &#42; values for each value site. The size of the array is NumValueSites.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00387" /><CodeLine lineNumber="387"><Highlight kind="comment">   &#42; Since NumValueSites is greater than zero, there is at least one</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00433" /><CodeLine lineNumber="433"><Highlight kind="comment">   &#42;The number of value profile kinds that has value profile data.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00434" /><CodeLine lineNumber="434"><Highlight kind="comment">   &#42; In this implementation, a value profile kind is considered to</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00496" /><CodeLine lineNumber="496"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The closure is designed to abstact away two types of value profile data:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00497" /><CodeLine lineNumber="497"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; - InstrProfRecord which is the primary data structure used to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00498" /><CodeLine lineNumber="498"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   represent profile data in host tools (reader, writer, and profile-use)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00499" /><CodeLine lineNumber="499"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; - value profile runtime data structure suitable to be used by C</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00500" /><CodeLine lineNumber="500"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   runtime library.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00501" /><CodeLine lineNumber="501"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00502" /><CodeLine lineNumber="502"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Both sources of data need to serialize to disk/memory-buffer in common</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00503" /><CodeLine lineNumber="503"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; format: ValueProfData. The abstraction allows compiler-rt&#39;s raw profiler</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00504" /><CodeLine lineNumber="504"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; writer to share the same format and code with indexed profile writer.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00505" /><CodeLine lineNumber="505"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00506" /><CodeLine lineNumber="506"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; For documentation of the member methods below, refer to corresponding methods</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00507" /><CodeLine lineNumber="507"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; in class InstrProfRecord.</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00710" /><CodeLine lineNumber="710"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00711" /><CodeLine lineNumber="711"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42; Magic number to detect file format and endianness.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00712" /><CodeLine lineNumber="712"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Use 255 at one end, since no UTF-8 file can use that character.  Avoid 0,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00713" /><CodeLine lineNumber="713"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; so that utilities, like strings, don&#39;t grab it as a string.  129 is also</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00714" /><CodeLine lineNumber="714"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; invalid UTF-8, and high enough to be interesting.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00715" /><CodeLine lineNumber="715"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Use &quot;lprofr&quot; in the centre to stand for &quot;LLVM Profile Raw&quot;, or &quot;lprofR&quot;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00716" /><CodeLine lineNumber="716"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; for 32-bit platforms.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00717" /><CodeLine lineNumber="717"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00718" /><CodeLine lineNumber="718"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define INSTR&#95;PROF&#95;RAW&#95;MAGIC&#95;64 (uint64&#95;t)255 &lt;&lt; 56 | (uint64&#95;t)&#39;l&#39; &lt;&lt; 48 | \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00719" /><CodeLine lineNumber="719"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">       (uint64&#95;t)&#39;p&#39; &lt;&lt; 40 | (uint64&#95;t)&#39;r&#39; &lt;&lt; 32 | (uint64&#95;t)&#39;o&#39; &lt;&lt; 24 |  \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00720" /><CodeLine lineNumber="720"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        (uint64&#95;t)&#39;f&#39; &lt;&lt; 16 | (uint64&#95;t)&#39;r&#39; &lt;&lt; 8 | (uint64&#95;t)129</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00721" /><CodeLine lineNumber="721"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define INSTR&#95;PROF&#95;RAW&#95;MAGIC&#95;32 (uint64&#95;t)255 &lt;&lt; 56 | (uint64&#95;t)&#39;l&#39; &lt;&lt; 48 | \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00722" /><CodeLine lineNumber="722"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">       (uint64&#95;t)&#39;p&#39; &lt;&lt; 40 | (uint64&#95;t)&#39;r&#39; &lt;&lt; 32 | (uint64&#95;t)&#39;o&#39; &lt;&lt; 24 |  \\</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00723" /><CodeLine lineNumber="723"><Highlight kind="preprocessor">        (uint64&#95;t)&#39;f&#39; &lt;&lt; 16 | (uint64&#95;t)&#39;R&#39; &lt;&lt; 8 | (uint64&#95;t)129</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00724" /><CodeLine lineNumber="724"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00725" /><CodeLine lineNumber="725"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42; Raw profile format version (start from 1). &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00726" /><CodeLine lineNumber="726"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define INSTR&#95;PROF&#95;RAW&#95;VERSION 10</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00727" /><CodeLine lineNumber="727"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42; Indexed profile format version (start from 1). &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00728" /><CodeLine lineNumber="728"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define INSTR&#95;PROF&#95;INDEX&#95;VERSION 12</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00729" /><CodeLine lineNumber="729"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42; Coverage mapping format version (start from 0). &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00730" /><CodeLine lineNumber="730"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define INSTR&#95;PROF&#95;COVMAP&#95;VERSION 6</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00731" /><CodeLine lineNumber="731"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00732" /><CodeLine lineNumber="732"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42; Profile version is always of type uint64&#95;t. Reserve the upper 32 bits in the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00733" /><CodeLine lineNumber="733"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; version for other variants of profile. We set the 8th most significant bit</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00734" /><CodeLine lineNumber="734"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; (i.e. bit 56) to 1 to indicate if this is an IR-level instrumentation</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00735" /><CodeLine lineNumber="735"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; generated profile, and 0 if this is a Clang FE generated profile.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00736" /><CodeLine lineNumber="736"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; 1 in bit 57 indicates there are context-sensitive records in the profile.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00737" /><CodeLine lineNumber="737"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The 54th bit indicates whether to always instrument loop entry blocks.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00738" /><CodeLine lineNumber="738"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The 58th bit indicates whether to always instrument function entry blocks.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00739" /><CodeLine lineNumber="739"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The 59th bit indicates whether to use debug info to correlate profiles.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00740" /><CodeLine lineNumber="740"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The 60th bit indicates single byte coverage instrumentation.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00741" /><CodeLine lineNumber="741"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The 61st bit indicates function entry instrumentation only.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00742" /><CodeLine lineNumber="742"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The 62nd bit indicates whether memory profile information is present.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00743" /><CodeLine lineNumber="743"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The 63rd bit indicates if this is a temporal profile.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00744" /><CodeLine lineNumber="744"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00745" /><CodeLine lineNumber="745"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define VARIANT&#95;MASKS&#95;ALL 0xffffffff00000000ULL</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00746" /><CodeLine lineNumber="746"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define GET&#95;VERSION(V) ((V) &amp; ~VARIANT&#95;MASKS&#95;ALL)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00747" /><CodeLine lineNumber="747"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define VARIANT&#95;MASK&#95;INSTR&#95;LOOP&#95;ENTRIES (0x1ULL &lt;&lt; 55)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00748" /><CodeLine lineNumber="748"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define VARIANT&#95;MASK&#95;IR&#95;PROF (0x1ULL &lt;&lt; 56)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00750" /><CodeLine lineNumber="750"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="preprocessor">#define VARIANT&#95;MASK&#95;INSTR&#95;ENTRY (0x1ULL &lt;&lt; 58)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00989" /><CodeLine lineNumber="989"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42; Map an (observed) memop size value to the representative value of its range.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00990" /><CodeLine lineNumber="990"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; For example, 5 -&gt; 5, 22 -&gt; 17, 99 -&gt; 65, 256 -&gt; 256, 1001 -&gt; 513 &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00992" /><CodeLine lineNumber="992"><Highlight kind="normal">InstrProfGetRangeRepValue(uint64&#95;t Value) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00993" /><CodeLine lineNumber="993"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">if</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> (Value &lt;= 8)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00994" /><CodeLine lineNumber="994"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The first ranges are individually tracked. Use the value as is.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00995" /><CodeLine lineNumber="995"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">return</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> Value;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00996" /><CodeLine lineNumber="996"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">else</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">if</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> (Value &gt;= 513)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00997" /><CodeLine lineNumber="997"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The last range is mapped to its lowest value.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00998" /><CodeLine lineNumber="998"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">return</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> 513;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00999" /><CodeLine lineNumber="999"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">else</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">if</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> (InstProfPopcountll(Value) == 1)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01000" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1000"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// If it&#39;s a power of two, use it as is.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01001" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1001"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">return</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> Value;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01002" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1002"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">else</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01003" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1003"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Otherwise, take to the previous power of two + 1</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01004" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1004"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">return</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> (UINT64&#95;C(1) &lt;&lt; (64 - InstProfClzll(Value) - 1)) + 1;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01005" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1005"><Highlight kind="normal">&#125;</Highlight></CodeLine>
